---
import ColorHysteresisGame from '../../components/ColorHysteresisGame.svelte';
import ColorHysteresisReveal from '../../components/ColorHysteresisReveal.svelte';
import ColorHysteresisAverageReveal from '../../components/ColorHysteresisAverageReveal.svelte';
import ColorHysteresisPopulationStrip from '../../components/ColorHysteresisPopulationStrip.svelte';
import ColorHysteresisTippingPointComparison from '../../components/ColorHysteresisTippingPointComparison.svelte';
import ColorHysteresisTheoryPoll from '../../components/ColorHysteresisTheoryPoll.svelte';
import BaseHead from '../../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';
import Header from '../../components/Header.astro';
import { SITE_TITLE } from '../../consts';
import { SHADES } from '../../lib/colorHysteresis';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
	<head>
		<BaseHead
			title={`Colors are vague — ${SITE_TITLE}`}
			description="An experiment in perceptual switch-points across a blue-to-green color gradient."
		/>
		<style>
			main {
				width: 960px;
			}
			.prose {
				width: 720px;
				max-width: 100%;
				margin: 0 auto;
			}
			.game {
				width: 100%;
				max-width: 960px;
				margin: 3em auto;
			}
			.prose ul,
			.prose ol {
				margin-bottom: 2em;
			}
			.reveal {
				padding-top: 1em;
			}
			.population h2 {
				margin-bottom: 1em;
			}
			.section-note {
				margin-bottom: 1.5em;
				color: rgb(var(--gray));
				font-size: 0.9rem;
				font-style: italic;
			}
			.signoff {
				margin-top: 1.5em;
			}
			.essay hr {
				margin: 2em 0;
			}
			.todo-marker {
				display: inline-block;
				margin-bottom: 1em;
				padding: 0.2em 0.6em;
				border-radius: 4px;
				background-color: rgba(var(--gray-light), 60%);
				color: rgb(var(--gray));
				font-size: 0.8em;
				font-weight: 700;
				letter-spacing: 0.05em;
				text-transform: uppercase;
			}
		</style>
	</head>
	<body>
		<Header />
		<main>
			<section class="prose intro">
				<h1>Colors are vague</h1>
				<p>You'll see a color, please click whichever one it looks like to you.</p>
			</section>

			<section class="game" aria-label="Color hysteresis experiment">
				<ColorHysteresisGame client:load shades={SHADES} />
			</section>

			<section class="prose reveal">
				<h2>Your results</h2>
				<ColorHysteresisReveal client:load />
			</section>

			<section class="prose essay">
				<p>
					Did you choose the same shade going forward and backward? If not, you're not the only
					one. And there may be a reason why.
				</p>
			</section>

			<section class="prose avg-results">
				<h2>Average results</h2>
				<p class="section-note">
					You experienced the colors in a random order — but to compare everyone fairly, we line up
					all the results as if each person had started from blue. Also, gap is defined as the
					average <strong>magnitude</strong> gap.
				</p>
				<ColorHysteresisAverageReveal client:load />
			</section>

			<section class="prose essay">
				<p>
					Psychologists Paul Égré, Vincent de Gardelle, and David Ripley were curious about how we
					interpret colors, and ran an <a href="http://paulegre.free.fr/Papers/voe.pdf" target="_blank"
						>experiment</a
					> similar to the one you just played. Depending on which direction the switch occurs, the
					effect goes by two different names:
				</p>
				<ul>
					<li>
						If you cling to whichever color you started with, taking longer to give it up, in both
						directions, that's called <strong>hysteresis</strong>.
					</li>
					<li>
						If instead you're quicker to abandon whichever color you started with, that's called <strong
							>enhanced contrast</strong
						>, or negative hysteresis.
					</li>
				</ul>
				<p>
					Égré, de Gardelle, and Ripley found a statistically significant enhanced-contrast effect,
					but only when people had to name the color out loud. When they ran a version with no
					language involved at all, just matching a shade to a visual of its nearer neighbor (pure
					blue vs. pure green), the effect
					disappeared entirely! That split is the interesting part. Whatever's happening here isn't
					really about how blue and green look. It's about what happens the moment we're forced to
					put a word on it.
				</p>
				<p>
					Now, it's interesting to see the psychological origins of this experiment. But what I
					find more interesting is the philosophical side. How did I make it to 22 years old and
					yet I still don't have a clear idea of what makes blue different from green? If I don't
					even agree with myself, can the general group at least come to a consensus? Tipping
					points, or the average of the two shades where each person switched, are one way we
					could explore that.
				</p>
			</section>

			<section class="prose population">
				<h2>Tipping points</h2>
				<ColorHysteresisTippingPointComparison client:load />
				<ColorHysteresisPopulationStrip client:load />
			</section>

			<section class="prose essay">
				<p>
					What I've thought about is that if there really were a defined tipping point sitting out
					there (a true, fixed boundary), you'd expect everyone to converge on more or less the
					same shade. We use these labels constantly, and we've had years of practice (colors were
					one of the first things we ever learned!). And yet, some spread always remains. A common
					answer does emerge, but it never quite collapses to a single point, and that persistent
					variation is what led me to wonder whether there's a real boundary to find in the first
					place.
				</p>
				<p>Naturally, I went down a rabbit hole and found a few competing theories:</p>
				<ol>
					<li>
						<strong>There's a real, sharp boundary, we just can't find it.</strong> On this view
						(Williamson, 1994), blue and green really do have a precise cutoff, we just lack the
						knowledge or tools to ever find it. If you're curious how this ties to chaos
						theory, <a href="https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/vagueness/#PhiChaPosVag" target="_blank"
							>Roy Sorensen's SEP entry on vagueness</a
						> digs into it in section 3.
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>There's no boundary to find, just a gap.</strong> On this view (Fine, 1975), the
						space between clearly blue and green isn't a hidden fact waiting to be discovered. It's
						a real gap: some shades are simply neither blue nor green, period. Philosophers call
						this <em>indeterminacy</em>.
					</li>
					<li>
						<strong>The categories overlap.</strong> On this view (Hyde, 1997; Smith, 2008), it's not
						that there's nothing there. Instead, borderline shades genuinely count as both colors
						at once, two categories overlapping rather than leaving a gap between them.
					</li>
				</ol>
			</section>

			<section class="prose essay">
				<p>Which explanation makes the most sense to you?</p>
				<ColorHysteresisTheoryPoll client:load />
			</section>

			<section class="prose essay">
				<p>
					As is true with most philosophy, there are many possible answers and no consensus in
					sight. Personally, I land somewhere between the theories that there's a sharp boundary
					that's out of our reach (1) and indeterminacy (2).
				</p>
				<p>
					And how do you operate in a world this vague? While I'm not entirely sure, the
					possibility of indeterminacy leaves me hesitant to ascribe labels to anything. I find
					it's natural to want to label and categorize everything, from people to aesthetics, but
					I've come to feel that impulse misses a lot of the nuance that makes life interesting.
					The more we treat the world as static and binary, the easier it is to end up boxed in,
					where change starts to feel impossible.
				</p>
				<p>
					So while I still haven't figured out where the boundaries lie for colors (or quite
					literally anything else), I've decided to just sit in the uncertainty, and to try seeing
					the world as fluid instead. And I may never find out if that's the right way to look at
					it. But for now, it's a lens that lets me live with a little more curiosity and a little
					more grace toward everything that stays undefined.
				</p>
				<hr />
				<p>
					I hope you enjoyed this little essay! Definitely not perfect, but a first attempt at
					turning the ideas in my brain into something tangible, and hopefully the first of a few.
				</p>
				<p>
					This deep dive started after I began noticing all sorts of fuzzy boundaries in
					miscellaneous parts of life. Music particularly always struck a chord (haha), and I began
					bending over backwards trying to figure out where one genre like 'Pop' ultimately becomes
					another like 'Rock'. As you may guess, I have yet to reach any sort of answer... so next,
					I hope to continue this series by following that music tangent, and exploring the
					boundaries (or lack thereof) between different genres and sounds.
				</p>
				<p>
					Thank you again for taking the time to read this, and if you have any feedback please
					feel free to let me know!
				</p>
				<p class="signoff">Best,<br /><em>Olivia</em></p>
			</section>
		</main>
		<Footer />
	</body>
</html>
